I wrote a short greentext for /adhg/ about the concept not long ago. Essentially, the central idea is that anthros are generally unimpressed with humans, in large part because they may have been designed and created to have greater strength or speed than humans, or better eyesight, and often have built-in weapons that humans lack. Anthros are generally unimpressed by most humans. And it is generally expected that if you want to get involved with one, you have to get her to take you seriously, and that means impressing her and her friends and family.

Carnivore species respect hunting prowess. Wolves, for example, are willing to consider you if you're willing to go on a hunt with them--and do it their way, Stone Age style. In some groups, if they like you or think you have potential, you'll have to go innawoods naked with them, but they'll spot you a flint-tipped spear. With other species it varies. You want an otter or dolphin, impress her with your swimming. You want to get with a horse, they generally want to see your athletic form, your strength and endurance. At the very least anthros want to see you're willing to make the effort and try. Some species are harder to impress than others. Different species have different cultures that tend to hold different traits and skills in esteem and of course they're all individuals too. But what impresses them is generally physical prowess and practical skills, not your ability to conjugate irregular French verbs or solve differential equations.
